<Page x:Class="Hardcodet.Wpf.Samples.Help.SQLParms"
	xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
	xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
	Title="SQLParms" 
	>
    <FlowDocumentReader ViewingMode="Scroll">
        <FlowDocument FontSize="20">
            <Paragraph>
                <Image Source="/Images/help1.png" Width="190" Height="190" Margin="0,0,30,0" />
                <Run FontSize="30" BaselineAlignment="Center">SQLParms</Run>

            </Paragraph>
            <Table CellSpacing="5" BorderThickness="1" BorderBrush="Black">
                <TableRowGroup>
                    <TableRow>
                        <TableCell>
                            <Paragraph>
                                <Image Source="/Images/SQLParms.PNG"  Margin="5,5,5,5"  HorizontalAlignment="Center" />
                            </Paragraph>
                        </TableCell>
                    </TableRow>
                </TableRowGroup>
            </Table>
            
            <Paragraph>
                SQL Parms are used to pass variables to a sql statement or sql stored procedure.  The Sql parm in the sql statement always begins with an @ sign.  The Name of the SQL Parm is how you refer to the SQL Parm in your script.  SPName is a primitive string that contains the variable name with the @ sign before it as it will be used in the SQL Statement. For example, the SPNAME for a variable for a person's first name might be @firstname. ParmType is a dropdownlist of sql variable types that indicate the data type for the parm. The ParmValue points to a primitive that will hold the value of the parameter. Here are the columns involved in SQLParms:
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph FontSize="14pt" >
                <Italic>
                    <Bold>
                        1. Name
                    </Bold>
                </Italic>
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph>
                Name is the name that will be used by the script to refer to the SQL Parm.
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph FontSize="14pt" >
                <Italic>
                    <Bold>
                2. SPName
                    </Bold>
                </Italic>
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph>
                SPName is a primitive string that contains the variable name with the @ sign before it as it will be used in the SQL Statement. For example, the SPNAME for a variable for a person's first name might be @firstname.
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph FontSize="14pt" >
                <Italic>
                    <Bold>
                        3. ParmType
                    </Bold>
                </Italic>
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph>
                ParmType is a dropdownlist of sql variable types that indicate the data type for the parm.
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph FontSize="14pt" >
                <Italic>
                    <Bold>
                        4. ParmValue
                    </Bold>
                </Italic>
            </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph>
                The ParmValue points to a primitive that will hold the value of the parameter.
            </Paragraph>


        </FlowDocument>
    </FlowDocumentReader>
</Page>
